# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1889-louisville-colonels-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1882 Louisville Eclipse season** was the first season as a Major League club for the franchise.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The team, which had played for several years as a semi-pro team, joined the new American Association league.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] They finished the season with a 42–38 record, good for third place.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1883 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 52–45 record, fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1884 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 68–40 record, third place in the American Association.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] There has been some debate over whom the manager of this club was, with some sources listing the club's starting second baseman, Joe Gerhardt, as manager for at least part of the year, with others crediting team official Mike Walsh with either all or part of the year.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] Guy Hecker started 75 games for the Eclipse in 1884 and won the American Association Pitching Triple Crown by leading the league in wins, with 52, strikeouts, with 385, and earned run average with 1.80.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The **1885 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The team (formerly the Louisville Eclipse) finished with a 53–59 record, tied for fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1886-louisville-colonels-season] The **1886 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1886-louisville-colonels-season] The team finished with a 66–70 record, fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1886-washington-nationals-season] The **1886 Washington Nationals** finished with a 28–92 record in the National League, finishing in last place in their debut season.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The **1889 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The team finished with a 27–111 record, last in the American Association.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The Colonels were the first Major League team to lose more than 100 games in a season.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The previous record for losses was 92, set by the Washington Nationals in 1886 and matched by the Cleveland Blues in 1887.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The record would be broken again in 1890 by the Pittsburgh Alleghenys, but remained the AA record until the league folded in 1891.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The Colonels also held a 24-game losing streak on the road, which not only was the longest losing streak on the road throughout the MLB-recognized American Association, but was also an infamous feat that would not be tied until the 2021 Arizona Diamondbacks matched it 132 years later in the MLB.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The team's owner, Mordecai Davidson, had taken control of the club in June 1888.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The Colonels had a bad season that year, and then in the offseason the cash-strapped Davidson made the team even worse by selling three of his best players (Elton "Ice Box" Chamberlain, catcher Lave Cross and outfielder Hub Collins).
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Davidson had managed the club himself for much of 1888, but he was criticized for that, so he brought in a new manager, Dude Esterbrook.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] He was also seeking a buyer for the team, as his own finances were precarious.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The 1889 season was a tumultuous one for the Colonels.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Manager Esterbrook fined several players, and was fired just ten games into the season.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Outfielder Jimmy "Chicken" Wolf was appointed team captain, although Davidson traveled with the team as well to ensure their good behavior – which proved quite unpopular.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Davidson continued to attempt to sell the club as the season progressed, but to no avail.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] On May 22, the team began a losing streak that would eventually reach 26 straight games, which still stands as the all-time Major League record as of 2024.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Most of the losses came during a stretch from May 24 until July 1 in which the team played just three games at home.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] During this time, Davidson began levying fines on his players for minor infractions, including routine errors on the playing field.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Things were no better from the perspective of the AA.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Financial difficulties had caused the team to miss payroll on three occasions, and the players alerted AA president Wheeler C.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] This led the AA to call a meeting to discuss the issue on June 14.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] On the way to the meeting, Davidson was confronted by his players calling for the rescinding of previous fines, threatening to strike if refused.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Davidson instead upped the ante, threatening to fine the players further if they lost.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The team was scheduled to play against the Baltimore Orioles on June 15.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The Colonels had 12 men available for duty that day, but six of them refused to play.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Three local semi-pro players, Walter Fisher, Mike Gaule and John Traffley, were recruited to join the remaining players on the field to allow the game to commence.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The resulting game was shortened to five innings by rain; Baltimore won it by a score of 4–2.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The six striking Louisville players were persuaded to call off their strike the next day, when the directors of the American Association agreed to review their grievances against Davidson.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Davidson met payroll on June 21, but only by accounting for new fines to the team's players.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] In some cases, the fines exceeded the players' salary, and they were told they owed the club money.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Star outfielder Pete Browning was fined $335, and total team fines came to $1,800, $1,200 of which was attributed to the walkout.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Guy Hecker began taking steps towards founding a branch of John Montgomery Ward's Brotherhood of Professional Base Ball Players for the AA.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] On June 24, Davidson hired local bouncer Buck McKinney, ostensibly as team manager.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] While Wolf continued to handle on-field duties, McKinney traveled with the team to keep an eye on the players for the owner.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] By July 2, however, another payroll was due, and when it became apparent that he would be unable to meet it, Davidson decided to turn the team over to the AA.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] He did so officially on July 5, at the same time that the players received their hearing from Wyckoff.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] On July 10, all previous fines were remitted, with the exception of those associated with the June 15 walkout.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] The team was sold to a consortium of ten Louisville businessmen who set about the task of rebuilding it.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] Late in the season a new manager, Jack Chapman, was hired.
[src:1889-louisville-colonels-season/1889-louisville-colonels-season] He guided the Colonels for the last seven games of the 1889 season, and continued to serve as the club's manager until June 20, 1892.
